<subSubSection pageId="149" pageNumber="910" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="149.[802,1395,1911,2340]" lastBlockId="149.[187,1394,2345,3090]" pageId="149" pageNumber="910">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[802,1049,2236,2261]" pageId="149" pageNumber="910">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 
<quantity box="[1237,1387,2236,2261]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.9" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="3.3" pageId="149" pageNumber="910" unit="mm" value="39.0" valueMax="45.0" valueMin="33.0">33-45 mm</quantity>
, tail 
<quantity box="[861,1014,2271,2300]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" metricValueMax="3.1" metricValueMin="2.7" pageId="149" pageNumber="910" unit="mm" value="29.0" valueMax="31.0" valueMin="27.0">27-31 mm</quantity>
, ear 
<quantity box="[1099,1250,2271,2300]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="149" pageNumber="910" unit="mm" value="16.5" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="15.0">15-18 mm</quantity>
, hindfoot 
<quantity box="[805,957,2311,2340]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="149" pageNumber="910" unit="mm" value="12.5" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="11.0">11-14 mm</quantity>
, forearm 277- 
<quantity box="[1175,1288,2311,2340]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="149" pageNumber="910" unit="mm" value="32.0">32 mm</quantity>
. Fur is thick and very silky; dorsally golden brown (hairs with grayish-black bases and golden tips); ventrally paler (hairs grayish black basally with off-white tips). Dorsal pelage extends sparsely onto wings, uropatagium, thumbs, and feet. Face is sparsely haired except long protuberant nostrils, which are naked. Ears are short and broad with smoothly convex anterior margins, notch on posterior margin, and a broadly rounded tip; tragus is long, narrow, and tapering toward pointed tip. Wing attaches to base offirst toe. Skull small and delicate, with very low rostrum. P? is much smaller than P*; crowns of C, are relatively low, about equal in height to P..
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
